WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.200
Hey there techies, welcome back to w3schools.com.

00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:06.760
Today we're diving into the rules of Python syntax,

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:07.720
let's get started.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:11.520
Quick recap on how to run Python on your own.

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:14.280
You can execute Python code directly in the command line

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:15.540
from the Python shell.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:20.960
Just type something like print, hello world, and hit enter.

00:00:20.960 --> 00:00:23.840
Your message is displayed right away.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:27.200
You can also create a Python file with the .pi extension

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:29.440
and run it from the command line.

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:31.280
You can name the file whatever you want,

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.520
but it must end with .pi.

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:37.320
Run the file with the Python command and the file location.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:39.960
For our examples, we use our own Python code editor

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:41.960
that you can run right from your browser,

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.200
no installation required.

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.760
That covers how to run Python.

00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:49.400
Now let's look at the rules for writing Python,

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:51.560
starting with indentation.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:54.400
In Python, indentation is crucial.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:56.200
In this example, we have an if statement

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:00.520
with a second line, print, five is greater than two.

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:03.720
The second line is indented with four spaces.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:06.280
This indentation tells Python that the second line

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:08.680
is part of the if statement block.

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:10.480
If you skip the indentation,

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:12.320
Python will throw a syntax error

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.760
or read them as two different statements.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.920
So always remember to indent your code properly.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:19.640
You can use different numbers of spaces,

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:21.720
but the standard is four.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:24.400
Just make sure you're consistent within the same block

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:26.000
because Python will throw an error

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.720
if you use different numbers of spaces

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:28.880
within the same block.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:32.760
Next up, variables.

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:36.160
In Python, you create variables by assigning values to them,

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:37.480
like this.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:40.640
Here, x is an integer variable with a value of five

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:44.560
and y is a string variable with the value hello world.

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:47.040
No need for a type declaration, simple and easy.

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:50.800
And don't forget about comments.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:54.240
They start with a hashtag and are great for documentation.

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.440
When Python sees a hashtag on a line,

00:01:56.440 --> 00:01:59.280
it will read the rest of that line as a comment.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:02.280
So you can write notes to yourself or others in your code.

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:03.200
Handy, right?

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:05.360
Thanks for watching.

